          "id": 38050,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">1-a, 2-b, 3-c, 4-d</span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Match the following codons with the correct amino acid they code for or their function in this specialized context:</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><img src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/Screenshot%202025-05-15%20190722.png\" width=\"440\" height=\"210\"></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q6276338",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 30445,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        1
      ],
      "solution": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Correct Answer: A. 1-b, 2-a, 3-d, 4-c</strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Explanation:</strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">1. UGA → B) Selenocysteine</span></p><ul style=\"list-style-type:disc;\"><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Normally: A stop codon.</span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Special context: With a specific SECIS element (Selenocysteine Insertion Sequence), UGA is redefined to insert selenocysteine.</span></li></ul><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Correct match: 1-b</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">2. UAG → A) Pyrrolysine</span></p><ul style=\"list-style-type:disc;\"><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Normally: A stop codon.</span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Special context: In certain bacteria, UAG can code for pyrrolysine, the 22nd amino acid.</span></li></ul><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Correct match: 2-a</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">3. AUG → D) Methionine</span></p><ul style=\"list-style-type:disc;\"><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Always: The standard start codon and codes for methionine.</span></li></ul><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Correct match: 3-d</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">4. UCA → C) Serine</span></p><ul style=\"list-style-type:disc;\"><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Always: Codes for serine under the standard genetic code.</span></li></ul><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Correct match: 4-c</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Other Options:</strong></span></p><ul><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option B</strong>. 1-b, 2-c, 3-d, 4-b</span><br><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">UAG does not code for serine; UCA does.</span><br><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">UCA doesn’t code for selenocysteine.</span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option C</strong>. 1-a, 2-d, 3-b, 4-c</span><br><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">UGA codes for selenocysteine, not pyrrolysine.</span><br><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">AUG codes for methionine, not selenocysteine.</span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option D</strong>. 1-a, 2-b, 3-c, 4-d&nbsp;is incorrect</span><br><br>&nbsp;</li></ul><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Educational Objective:</strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Understand the standard genetic code and recognize exceptions like:</span></p><ul style=\"list-style-type:disc;\"><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">UGA coding for selenocysteine in the presence of SECIS.</span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">UAG coding for pyrrolysine in some organisms.</span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">AUG as the universal start codon for methionine.</span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">UCA coding for serine in standard contexts.</span></li></ul>",
      "correct_choice_id": 38047,
