        },
        {
          "id": 38010,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Polyalanine</span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Considering a synthetic mRNA composed entirely of adenine nucleotides (poly A), what type of polypeptide would this mRNA sequence code for?</span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q9904318",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 30443,
      "difficulty_level": "difficult",
      "subjects_id": [
        1
      ],
      "solution": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Ans. A. Polylysine</strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Explanation:</strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">A synthetic mRNA consisting entirely of adenine nucleotides (poly A) would be read by the ribosome as repeated <strong>AAA codons</strong>. According to the genetic code, the codon <strong>AAA</strong> specifies the amino acid <strong>lysine</strong>.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Therefore, during translation, a poly A mRNA would direct the ribosome to synthesize a <strong>polypeptide made entirely of lysine residues</strong> — referred to as <strong>polylysine</strong>.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">This was demonstrated in early experiments by Nirenberg and colleagues, who used synthetic mRNAs to decipher codon-amino acid relationships.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Other Options:</strong></span></p><ul style=\"list-style-type:disc;\"><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option B. Polyglycine:</strong> Glycine is coded by GGU, GGC, GGA, or GGG — not AAA.</span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option C. Polyproline:</strong> Proline is coded by CCU, CCC, CCA, and CCG — not by adenine-only codons.</span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option D. Polyalanine:</strong> Alanine is encoded by GCU, GCC, GCA, and GCG — again, not AAA.</span></li></ul><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Educational Objective:</strong></span></p><ul style=\"list-style-type:disc;\"><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Poly A → Lysine</strong></span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Poly C → Proline</strong></span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Poly G → Glycine</strong></span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Poly U → Phenylalanine</strong></span></li></ul><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Ref</strong>: Harper 30/e page 415.</span></p>",
      "correct_choice_id": 38007,
